	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Some economists fear the labor market is a different sort of animal these days, meaning the old expectations about labor-market behavior could be wrong. For one thing, technological improvements have led to a staggering surge in productivity, meaning employers are able to milk much more work out of fewer workers.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Still, this doesn't mean U.S. employers are just never going to hire people again. Eventually, stronger growth should lead to a pickup in jobs. <br />
<br />
The big question is the timing of that pickup, and many economists think it will take several months before the economy is growing fast enough to create 125,000 or so jobs per month, the level most economists believe is necessary to push down the unemployment rate. <br />
<br />
&quot;The second half will show some better growth. Will that be sustained past the second half? For that, two things have to happen: we have to see a pickup in business spending, and the labor market has to stabilize and improve, creating permanent employment,&quot; said former Federal Reserve economist Wayne Ayers, now chief economist at Fleet Boston Financial. &quot;We don't expect to see that until year-end.&quot; <hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
Sounds pretty positive to me. We cannot measure the employment rate using the variables of the past. People, employers, are finding ways to cut the labor force. Heck, I remember when people we bitching about the new &quot;robots&quot; automating car manufacturing and how the new technology was going to lay off thousands.<br />
<br />
As said before, the employement level is the last to improve in a improving economy. We really do not know how employers will spend the money. Will they &quot;upgrade&quot; tech so they can hire less (automating the process) or are we counting on them getting the job done the old fashion way with man-power? Who knows.. Employers are not obligated to hire just because there is a high unemployment rate...esp if they can get the job done without the added cost.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
