	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>There was a fundamental change in our economy that took place.<br />
<br />
From my understanding a tax cut at any time is not always in the best interest of the country. There are times that it is in great interest to have a tax cut and there are times that it is detrimental. Also the type of tax cut is pertinent.  Sometimes a tax cut is needed to stimulate spending and sometimes its needed to stimulate business. Sometimes its needed to stimulate both. <br />
The problem is that the economy was different when Bush took office then it is today. He promised on his campaign trail a tax cut. At that time one wasn't needed as it was pure political posturing. It was a reaction to his father's unpopularity of raising taxes and it was also a pander to get some votes. He followed through on the tax cut that he had proposed before he was elected. How was what was good then still relative now? I contend that Bush did this tax cut purely for political gain and not because it was helpful to the economy.<br />
<br />
Bush claiming the economy is good is repeating the same mistake his father made that cost Bush 1 the election. Conservatives think it was the &quot;no new taxes&quot; lie that cost Bush 1 the election but that's not what lost it for him. It was the fact that he insisted the economy was good while people were out of work. Bush 2 is doing the same thing. My suggestion is that Bush 2 stop spinning the economy and learn what's going wrong with it so he can fix it. He has a tendency to not learn much about anything and makes base decisions without knowing what the outcomes will be. Quite frankly he doesn't think things through.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
