	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><i>Originally posted by Rheaton </i><br />
<b>Sounds pretty positive to me. We cannot measure the employment rate using the variables of the past. People, employers, are finding ways to cut the labor force. Heck, I remember when people we bitching about the new &quot;robots&quot; automating car manufacturing and how the new technology was going to lay off thousands.<br />
<br />
As said before, the employement level is the last to improve in a improving economy. We really do not know how employers will spend the money. Will they &quot;upgrade&quot; tech so they can hire less (automating the process) or are we counting on them getting the job done the old fashion way with man-power? Who knows.. Employers are not obligated to hire just because there is a high unemployment rate...esp if they can get the job done without the added cost. </b><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
I don't think it is at all positive to those who are unemployed. Further, I think the market is reflecting the unease investors have over the potential of another recession. I think some worry that spending over the next few months will not be strong enough to alleviate investor worries, especially as we move towards the holidays.<br />
<br />
Another thing that interests me is the increased debt held by Americans. It reminds me of the tax-cut and spend politics of the Reagan administration during which the average debt amongst Americans hit all time highs (which usually increases defaulted debts). <br />
<br />
My point is that we will be more likely to take our advance in the child credit to pay down some debt, or to tuck away in the matress until things pick up economically, before we go on any shopping sprees. I think the average American is a bit worried about the economy and if Bush wants re-election, then he will have to do something more than what he is doing now domestically. Otherwise, he will likely make the same mistakes his father made, as Bumble rightly points out.</p>
	
	
	
