	<p>Bumble, where to begin...?<br />
<br />
You feel that bush followed through with tax cuts for political gain and to avenge his daddy? That speaks volumns.<br />
<br />
I believe that one day we will read about G.W. Bush and how masterfully he balanced: The economy; the war on terror; the war in Iraq. We will hear how close the U.S. economy was on the brink of destruction and somehow Bush's policies managed to get everything done and do it with considerably good results.<br />
<br />
Bush enters office and takes over a failing economy. Yup, failing. Actually the last half year of Clinton showed signs that the economy was on a downhill slope. Bush stumped on tax cuts to give people back &quot;their&quot; money.. but also to stimulate the economy at that time..which needed it (and still does). This isnt about millions of people pumping a grand back into the economy. Its about lowering taxes so that people and companies, in the long run, will invest more and buy more. If you have ever owned or ran even a small buisness you would understand how just the smallest tax code modification can affect how you do things.<br />
<br />
Bush is not buying votes..but even if he were, the results would be just as positive. The fact that the &quot;surplus&quot; durning Clinton's rein was so high proved that the U.S. taxpayers where over-taxed. IS there a need for surplus after all the bills are paid?<br />
<br />
One valid point you do make is that Bush may have needed to re-think things since the economy was in bad shape. Perhaps it wasnt &quot;prudent&quot; to take money of out of the government at a time when so many programs need those funds. It was a gamble... and one he was forced to take. If he didnt follow through with the tax cuts, the effects could have been an even deeper hardening of investments, etc. Employers and investors could have really hunkered down for the long haul, thus stalling growth even more.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
