	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><i>Originally posted by bumbleroot </i><br />
<b>Bush's problem is his lack of pragmatism. He doesn't think anything through. This was obvious with his post war planning. It is obvious on his lack of focus on Al Qaeda. Even I, who is not the President, foresaw the problems we would face. His decisions are based upon base knowledge of how things really work and not from a thorough knowledge.  He makes decisions based upon anger and fear. As far as history and Bush's balancing of his job- I might suggest that he has seen the loss of more jobs than any president in this country. This won't show his economic prowess. At some point he has to take credit for that. He has overseen the largest drop in deficit in our history. <br />
I should suggest that Bush still doesn't get it. He is as out of touch as his father was. That is why his father lost the election. The &quot;Bubbaness&quot; of Clinton was what won his elections. Bush saying the economy is better when people are losing jobs is a mistake. He would be better not spinning it and admitting or having some plan or idea to get jobs. His entire premise has been to cut taxes and let the rest take care of itself. Its just not that simple. </b><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
I disagree. Before we started the war in Iraq, I remember reading and hearing how it was going to cost thousands of lives... we would be there for years fighting in the trenches and never &quot;really&quot; be able to sieze control of Iraq. I dont think Bush should get all the credit though. Rummy orchstrated much of the war (along with others). Besides, taking over Iraq has been on the drawing board for years (Bush Sr. started it, Clinton enhanced it and Rummy perfected it).<br />
<br />
Im not really sure what people expect when it comes to economic turn-about. Six months? A year? Two years? I suppose its a realitive to how much damage it sustained and where. Unless we can truely measure the damage done, and the measures needed to correct and repair, we may never know the true balance. Its a scarry thing when both sides tells us that the other is wrong and that they know the true way. Someone is gonna be wrong!<br />
<br />
Economic foundations, esp as large a the U.S., takes a considerable amount of building. Does anyone truely think that Clinton established the economic foundation in the 90s? If it were a good foundation, wouldnt it have withstood better? Im not pinning anything on Clinton here.. he did ok with what he had to deal with. But the truth of the matter was that he aquired a economy that had been building a strong and steady foundation (Reagan and Bush Sr.) for years.. .much like the one we see in the making now.<br />
<br />
Right now, esp as we get towards an election year, we will hear and read people telling us: How bad it has been; how bad it could have been; and the &quot;what ifs&quot; and &quot;we <i>could</i> be heading down hill&quot;. Show me some truely unbias people who is saying that the current economic trend is only going to get worse. Someone who can back it with numbers.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
