</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Im not really sure what people expect when it comes to economic turn-about. Six months? A year? Two years?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>The only one's that care about the time it takes are economists and politicians and spin doctors. People don't care, they just want to be told the truth. Denying there is a recession or saying the economy is strong when you lose jobs is a bad thing to do. Bush should say why we lost the jobs and how he can fix that.<br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Does anyone truely think that Clinton established the economic foundation in the 90s? If it were a good foundation, wouldnt it have withstood better?<hr size="1" /></blockquote>If you remember in 1992, Al Gore's pet project was on streamlining the government and developing the &quot;Information Superhighway&quot; as they called it. This did give us quite an economic boost although it wasn't a strong boost that Gore/Clinton gave us.<br />
What we fail to remember is that people left their jobs and got trained in computer programming or systems analysis or other things like that and those jobs they were in went away. Now that the high tech jobs have taken their natural correction the other jobs are gone as well. Bush needs to have a plan to develop and create some of those jobs or some new type of job. Until he does, the hemorrhaging will continue.<br />
<br />
As far as the results from the Iraq war. Everyone said they weren't sure what the results would be. We all knew that the Iraqi army was weaker than they were in 91 because of all of the sanctions. We also knew that going in and simply taking out a government but not restoring something of their choosing in its place would also be messy. The criticism (and its from both parties) is that we aren't being told what the plans are because there just isn't any. I don't think anyone thought Iraq would take long to fall to our forces. I was a little surprised it took as long as it did. <br />
<br />
I felt in the early days of the war that something wasn't right. We were losing a lot of soldiers from accidents and very few from combat even though we faced many combat situations. I believed that a lot of these &quot;accidental deaths&quot; were the result of guerilla attacks but they were &quot;Jessica Lynched&quot; to sound less harmful to our cause. I felt the Bushies didn't want us to know that there were guerilla attacks because it would lessen support for this war. My instincts were right.  They have tried to downplay the guerilla attacks. I believe the Bush administration did expect guerilla attacks but they have no plan on how to combat them. I also feel they know that a continued guerilla war would look too much like Vietnam therefore they try to make it seem less like a guerilla war.<br />
<br />
Now to compound things there are reports from soldiers of a pneumonia like disease. Some soldiers have died from it. The strange thing is that there is no pattern to who has the disease. The soldiers with it were at different places during the war.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
