<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Laoke</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Registered User<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Nov 2002<br />
	Location: New Zealand<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><i>Originally posted by bumbleroot </i><br />
<b>Speaking of their computers they were still in DOS, which I'm sure isn't the most efficient system for running a business.</b><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
  Not necessarily.  I work for a government ministry here in New Zealand in the IT department.  Untill this time last year, we were running Windows 3.11 on the desktop (effectively the same as DOS : ), and Windows NT 3.51 on our servers.  Why?<br />
<br />
  Because untill Office 2000 hit we could read any documents sent to us from outside the Ministry, and the existing desktop / servers were stable as a rock.  Virii would hit us and bounce... the more modern Outlook virii for example simply can't work in our old environment.  The advantages of upgrading were nil, and the disadvantages quite high... untill we <b>had</b> to upgrade to allow our users more functionality &amp; the ability to read Office 2000 files.<br />
<br />
  I'd wager that the DMV system is a custom application.  I'd wager even higher that it works fine as is.  The whole 'not processing for a month' thing strikes me more as a beaurcratic regulation more than an IT fault... and the other consideration is that not many people can hack a DOS system because most scripts and the like simply won't work in that sort of environment.<br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" /><b>Its fairly obvious that government employees only have to do their 8 hours a day and go home. There are no rewards for efficiency or any ability to get things done more efficiently. If they were more efficient our tax dollars would be much better used. That is why some people have outsourced some of the government jobs.  I have proposed on here and I still believe that government agencies need to develop their own sources of income. As it is they are tax based and not based upon performing competitively. A system of using tax dollars to ween agencies off of reliance upon tax dollars and into a self-sufficient entity should start occurring in my opinion. The post office whether we like it or not does more for each citizen and more timely and it does it better than most organizations. Why? Because it is self-sufficient. </b><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
  True, as far as it stands, but how do you make something like the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade self-sufficient?  Sure, you could move to a 'user-pays' system, but a lot of the International treaties &amp; the like negociated by the Ministry benefit the whole country.  How are you going to assign a dollar value to something like an extradition treaty?  Or, in the case of Health, on someones life?  Or on the price of getting someone employed and off welfare?<br />
<br />
  A better way of doing it is simply this:  holding governmental staff responsible for their success &amp; failures.  reward them with <b>real</b> salaries, and if they don't perform <b>fire</b> them.  From my experience of working in the public sector, this simply doesn't happen.  I'm fortunate:  our IT depatment pays private sector rates for IT work so that we don't have staff retention problems, but if we paid public sector rates... I'd be looking at an effective pay drop of 10-15%.<br />
<br />
  They drone on and on about how our policy staff are rewarded by travel, and by making a difference, and other non-tangible benefits of the job.  But you know what the absolute reason people stay here is?  Job security.  They know that unless they're caught buggering a sheep on security camera within the Ministry's buildings, there is no way they're going to get fired.<br />
<br />
  Guess what sort of mindset that encourages?<br />
<br />
Laoke</p>
	
	
	
	
	
