<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>bumbleroot</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Registered User<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Dec 2002<br />
	
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>The problem with the economy is clear. Unfortunately I don't think Bush wants to recognize it.<br />
We are losing White Collar Jobs overseas. This is more efficient and makes businesses more powerful and wealthy. It serves only the investors well. Quite frankly this is not a problem, but an opportunity if its handled correctly. Lee Iacocca took an approach in the 80s of promoting cars built in America as opposed to Japan. As a result, the quality of cars improved and GM sales soared while foreign car sales fell. The opportunities for businesses to start up is great in America right now, they just aren't being exploited and the sales pitch isn't developed yet. As a president there isn't much one can do other than propose initiatives like tax cuts to fix things and also be a leader. Tax cuts won't put White Collar workers in America back to work. It will only give the companies money to spend on being more efficient. <br />
What Bush can do is start a campaign that encourages people to do business with All-American companies. He can begin by telling us the truth about how American businesses are going overseas with their jobs.  He has to stand up against businesses to start showing Americans what is being done so the opportunities can start happening. There are conservatives that are Nationalistic and there are liberals that are pro-worker. Bush has a golden opportunity to sell this well to the American people and as a result the businesses will start coming back to America as other startups see the opportunity.<br />
I can't think of anyway that Bush wouldn't gain from this approach. It would bring in a good bit of new voters for his re-election. It would echo the anti-big business sentiment of the people. It would solidify and give him a fair amount of new voters on his side. It would also strengthen our economy as competition would grow.<br />
I feel that Bush won't do this because he is so blatantly big business. However, we must all remember this one fact. Not a single business has ever had a vote in an election. He serves the people and only us.<br />
<br />
I am not anti-business or anti-big business. Knowing what I've read recently I believe that there is a problem with big business and workers. I had felt that the approach might be to strengthen unions to counteract this problem. I don't think that this is the best solution though as many union workers price themselves out of a job. In a nutshell this is kind of the problem that we are facing now.  It is a prime political opportunity and since Bush has the bully pulpit it is his approach to take until someone else beats him to the punch.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><a href="report.php?s=0ee418dff8d682ff6557d36ca99e4dc1&amp;p=155141">Report Post</a> | IP: <a href="postings.php?s=0ee418dff8d682ff6557d36ca99e4dc1&amp;do=getip&amp;p=155141">Logged</a></div>
	
	<!-- / message -->
		
	</td>
