Agree and disgree.  <br />
<br />
I agree with the idea of using our military to help patrol our borders.   I would make our borders with Canada and Mexico military bases.  These areas would be patrolled by military members while the border patol would focus their attention on the cities.   Plop an aircraft carrier in the Gulf of Mexico to assist the Coast Guard.<br />
<br />
I disagree with the idea of isolationism.   Keeping our forces &amp; supplies forward deployed allows us to more quickly respond to situations around the world.   Also, by having our forces in a position to quickly respond makes it less likely any potential enemy would attack our allies.<br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />I would cut government spending and increase taxes to pay off the deficit. <hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
Where are you going to start the cuts ??  Welfare ?? Social Security ??  If you want to cut those, then I'm all behind you.   It's easy to say &quot;cut&quot;, but you have to make the hard choices on what gets cut.   Also, when you make cuts in government, you are putting more people on unemployment.<br />
<br />
Increase taxes on everyone ??  Or just the rich ??<br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Next would be a large downsizing of the IRS (involving the abolition of tax audits on those making under 100K per year).<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
I would also downsize the IRS, but for a different reason.  I am an advocate of a &quot;flat tax&quot;.   Everyone pays the same tax, whether you make $10,000 a year or $10 million.   There are ZERO tax deductions.    The IRS just becomes a collection agency and enforcement agency to hit the cheats.<br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Pulling back our troops around the world, downsizing government, cutting spending, and increasing taxes would quickly eliminate the deficit and bring up the economy.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
Pulling back troops could save money in the short term, but cost us big time in the long run.   An ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure.<br />
<br />
Downsizing the goverment is usually easier said than done.  Congressman will fight tooth and nail to make sure the cuts don't happen in their districts.   Unemployment goes up as government employees are fired in droves.<br />
<br />
Increasing taxes is a sure way to slow down the economy.   Higher taxes means we don't have as much money to spend, so we buy less.  Factory orders go down and, once again, more people are on unemployment.<br />
<br />
In the short term, I think your plan would work nicely.  In the long run, we could be in real trouble with the high unemployment rates you create and increase in world conflicts resulting from a lack of U.S. presence abroad.  <br />
<br />
But, like I said, I do agree with you on using military to patrol our borders, but I wouldn't use our oversease troops to pull this off.  It is just too risky.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
