<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>bumbleroot</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Registered User<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Dec 2002<br />
	
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Bush pursued the tax cuts as if he had a mandate. He didn't have a mandate. The American people did not give him more votes. There were more people willing to accept a Clinton/Gore continuation than not accept one. The tax cut just wasn't on everyone's mind and it wasn't a mandate.<br />
I believe I have shown on other posts that because of Bush's wavering views of the deficit he has no idea on how to do things economically. Using the same logic he uses, every company should give their employees bonuses because their profits went up. Can you understand how this would hurt a company and how they would not be able to grow their revenues? What's even worse is that the government has no other source of income other than taxes.  I have not yet seen a reasonable reason to give tax cuts back to the people other than it being a well-liked idea. Shit, I'm sure 99% of employees would vote themselves a bonus if they could- the American people would do the same thing. That doesn't mean its the right move. A tax cut is more of a popular idea than it is a sensible idea.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><a href="report.php?s=0ee418dff8d682ff6557d36ca99e4dc1&amp;p=155428">Report Post</a> | IP: <a href="postings.php?s=0ee418dff8d682ff6557d36ca99e4dc1&amp;do=getip&amp;p=155428">Logged</a></div>
	
