<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Lurikeen</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Pinko Commie<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Nov 2002<br />
	Location: Not here!<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Rheaton</b><br /><i>Why increase taxes? Ok, so the national debt needs to be addressed (and should be). But for what else would the tax $ be spent on? More government programs? ITs one way or its the other. Either you increase taxes to pay for government programs... or you cut the programs so you can afford them with what revenues are collected.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
You just stated why we should increase taxes. To eliminate debt. All of us know that is what has to be done. Do you increase your debt load at home and seek a pay cut? When you want to pay off debt faster do you throw less money at the debt?<br />
<br />
Further your disjunct is not the case. It is not one way or the other. We can (and have) cut spending and increase taxes with a good result. We don't have to spend the increased revenue on new programs.<br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Although many do not believe this, the reason behind Bush's tax cuts is to stave off the current economic trend. For the last 15 or so years the tax payers have paid too much... And now we are seeing the results.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
Sorry but let me put this to you plainly: bullshit! Bush hasn't a <i>reason</i> behind his tax cuts which is obvious from his 2001 round of tax debilitation.<br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />The &quot;surplus&quot; was ungodly.. meaning we overpaid obviously. Durning the 00' election the economy had begun its downhill slide after being in a neutral state for more then a year. Itswas obvious that with all the surplus, and with the economy beginning to show signs, that we needed to get that money back into the hands of the taxpayers.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
No it was not obvious. The economic wheel had turned. Having a surplus now would greatly strengthen the economy. We would have more money to enrich our current ailing domestic problems. Conservatives are keen on pointing out that government should be run like a business. Well, then let's run it like a business. Successful businesses aren't those in bankruptcy! In fact, successful business owners (and CEOs) understand that there must be some cash in the pot to spend at all times.<br />
<br />
Conservatives <i>really don't believe</i> government should be treated like a business. If they really believed that then they would want government to be successful and the measure of success in the private world is growth! Conservatives want government to shrink (except for the military). They want government to be anemic. <br />
<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />No one knew that 9-11 would happen thus forcing us to spend money for the war on terror. Bush should have rethought this about his tax cuts.. I think the American people would have understood. The war in Iraq will pay for itself over time... so thats more like an investment (yeah, whatever). But this Dept. Homeland Security is a nightmare! I honeslty cannot see betterment of protection coming from this thing.. good grief!<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
I agree with you on the Office of Homeland Security. They should axe that mo fo!<br />
<br />
It is debatable as to what the government knew prior to 9/11 and if it was actionable knowledge. However, if the federal government had been working on a surplus and keeping it, then we could afford the war on terror. But another problem is even Bush is making the mistake of thinking that throwing money at a problem is the solution. People understand that spending and taxing responsibly, and with accountability, is necessary. People get pissed off when the feds aren't transparent with their spending, since it looks like they are hiding money from us!<br />
<br />
We also need to start electing politicians who aren't afraid to cut into favorite beauracracies! Why think that by cutting welfare we will get a new windfall of money? We won't, but if we eliminate a good portion of our government agencies we will see the money! We should be downsizing the &quot;corporate government&quot; starting by eliminating many of the middle management positions, and freezing hiring to allow attrition to work.<br />
<br />
Finally, if I had a wish list I could submit to congress, I would include in it getting rid of the electoral college in favor of the popular vote. Right now our Presidential candidates lobby certain states in order to get their votes. That includes wheeling and dealing with the Congressmen of those states and ensuring they are re-elected. Wheeling and dealing with the industry of those state and ensuring they get what they want. And why do they do that? Because the candidates know that money can potentially buy just enough votes to win all the electoral points for any given state. If we bring the weight of victory to the popular vote, then candidates would need to go directly to the people... not to particular states. This is a bigger issue for me than term limits which most politicians renege on any way making it worthless.</p>
	
	
	
